      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Gift of Life, Even at the End</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sarah Spikes letter observes that physicians are now learning what veterinarians know, that ability to enjoy life depends not only on diagnosis but on the individual (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>David A. Shaywitz (Op-Ed, Sept. 19) reveals that doctors are learning to deal with something that veterinarians have had to face all along. No matter how certain one is of the outcome of a disease, the path to that outcome should be left up to the people involved.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>David A. Shaywitz (Op-Ed, Sept. 19) reveals that doctors are learning to deal with something that veterinarians have had to face all along. No matter how certain one is of the outcome of a disease, the path to that outcome should be left up to the people involved.</p>
        <p>There are no statistics that accurately report how many happy times a dog, a cat or a horse will share with a master in the final months of life. If it were right to give up as soon as the terminal nature of a disease was clear, all dogs with a diagnosis of cancer would be euthanized on the spot. We do not do this because we know that the ability to enjoy life, even while aware that the end is imminent, depends not only on the diagnosis but also on the individual.</p>
        <p>SARAH SPIKES  Chevy Chase, Md., Sept. 19, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a veterinarian.</p>
      </block>
